segments.text: Go ahead.
Is it ready to go?
Well, after we bought this car, people come in the yard to see it.
Some of them say it wouldn't last.
Some of them thought it was all right.
But I think we drove it about 10 years.
Is it going?
It's going fine.
Go ahead.
And, of course, then they made things to last.
They didn't make it to wear out and go buy a new one the next day.
And there has been so many things now, though, that we didn't have then.
I can look back in my kitchen.
When I first kept house, everything was hard.
I had a wood stove.
We didn't buy stuff already prepared to eat.
We had to fix it.
And now, I think about the young generation.
All convenience in the world, they've got it.
And I don't know, they don't keep house like I did when I was raising my first children.
And washed, I always had help.
I always had a colored woman to help me.
And she washed on the washboard.
and iron with a flat iron, get that iron hot.
She'd build up a fire out in the yard with wood, and she'd put the iron in front of that and get it hot, and that's the way she ironed.
And now they have electric iron, and everything's perma-pressed.
Then everything was starched, stiff as a poker.
Things have come a long, long way, I can tell you.
At last, they have really made it easy on the housewife.
Do you think it's good or bad?
Well, I'll tell you what.
In a way, it's good.
And in a way, it is not.
It has made the young housewife lazy.
Maybe because she doesn't have to do as much work.
She don't have no hard work to do.
And they have washing machines.
And most every, now I don't like a dryer.
Why is that?
Is it stop?
Can I start?
Yeah, go ahead.
I'll tell you my objection to a dryer.
They burn the clothes, then the clothes is not pretty and white.
But I'll say this, it may be because I'm old fashioned.
You can't teach hardly an old dog new tricks.
And for 83 years, in fact, the seventh day of May, I'll be keeping house 61 years.
That's quite a long time.
And that's a long time to have to change.
Now, I will admit, I've got all convenience.
Yes, I've got it.
And I appreciate it and I enjoy it.
But don't think that I don't think so many times of things that I have done or we have done, rather.
Not I myself, but everybody else did the same thing.
Like what?
Well, look, now, everything, I even have an electric coffee pot.
You've got electric toaster.
You've got electric, just everything in the world in your kitchen now is electric.
I used to make my coffee in a pot, a coffee pot, put it on the stove,
and boil those grounds, push it off and let it set a while, and then pour that coffee in another pot.
That was coffee.
Well, now I either use electric percolator or drippolator.
What kind of cooking facilities, you know, say stove or oven or whatever did you have?
I had a wood stove.
For cooking, too?
Yes, sir, a wood stove.
And don't you forget it, that that's the best cooking in the world on a wood stove.
Now everything's cooked quick, quick.
Get it out of the deep freeze and pop it in the stove and cook it quick.
Did you, back in your family, when you grew up as a child, how did you heat your house?
Well, we had fireplaces.
Was it pretty cold up in Tennessee?
Oh, in Tennessee, people almost, they still have fireplaces there because they're on account of the weather.
Is that cold up there?
Oh, me, yes, it's cold there.
And they had wood stoves, of course.
People now, they have modern homes, I understand now, but the majority of people have fireplaces.
Yeah, fireplaces are a thing to have anywhere now.
Yeah, fireplaces now, just like even in Texas now, people building new homes, they have fireplaces.
Yeah, yeah.
Because, and of course, in my day, wood was cheap.
When I moved to Hearn, we, that old house that I sold last year, well, there was fireplaces there.
And then wood got higher and got to where you'd have to hire it and cut and everything while we had it closed up and got gas heaters.
I didn't know there was a fireplace over there.
Oh, yeah.
It was closed up.
There was two of them.
There was one in that north bedroom and one in the living room.
Oh, no.
Even my baby girl, we had it closed up.
She don't remember us having fireplace, and she's getting on up there herself.
Well, times has changed so much.
Another thing with teenagers, they congregate at one's house.
And they'd play cards.
They'd play dominoes.
And they would have a record player.
And they'd dance.
Was it crank record player?
Yeah.
It was called a phonograph.
You had a great big horn.
And you'd turn that thing.
And you'd put a record on there.
There's records.
And the children, they didn't think about getting in a car and riding out yonder, and there wasn't always a car wreck and things then.
Well, my first children, I had two sets of children, same mother and daddy.
The first four were great big children when I had these four little girls, and they still say they're four little girls.
And they didn't study about going, for they had horse and birdie.
They met at one another's house.
And now they don't go to one another's house.
They get in a car and go off somewhere and have a car wreck and somebody get killed.
I think that's one thing, the way that makes time so hard is the way people let their children do now.
I think they've brought a whole lot of it on themselves.
by not being economical.
Now, you take this crisis that we're going through with gas.
There's plenty of gas and plenty of oil.
It's somewhere else.
But we have brought it on ourselves, a whole lot of it.
I'll tell you, the majority of people have took living for granted that I'm supposed to have this.
I don't think that's right, what you're supposed to have.
God don't owe you nothing.
Amen to that.
I agree with you.
But a lot of people think so.
God owes them a living.
This is me.
Why can't I have that?
You can have it if you work for it, if you're well and can.
Of course, there's some people that can't.
And I'll tell you another thing that's changed.
People used to help each other.
If a neighbor got sick, I'd go over and I'd get their clothes, and we'd wash and iron them, take them to them.
And we used to make homemade bread.
Make a great big pan of homemade bread, bake a hen in dressing, and take it to the family.
People now don't do that.
They don't love one another like they used to.
They don't care.
I'll tell you the way the world is now.
Just so me and mine is the swimming, you can sink.
Oh, there's been lots of changes.
What kind of a roads facility did you have around here when y'all first came here?
Oh, we had dirt roads.
All of them were dirt?
No paved highways?
No.
I forgot what year it was, but I was living on Market Street when they built this highway.
Oh, that's what I was going to ask.
Highway 6 didn't exist when you first came here then.
Huh?
You mean Highway 6 didn't exist when you first came here?
Oh, it was a road, yes.
It was like gravel, you know.
It wasn't paved?
It wasn't a mud road.
It was gravel like from Dallas on into Houston.
It wasn't paved?
No, no, no, no, no.
And then they paved.
And it was narrow.
Of course, I reckon they thought cars wasn't going to get plentiful like they are now.
And they made it so narrow.
And I think that's one reason we had so many car wrecks years ago.
When did they pave it?
Oh, I don't remember what year it was when they paved it.
It was in the early 40s when they paved it.
And then, of course,
I won't live to see it, but probably you will, and my grandchildren maybe, that there will be four-way highways everywhere.
And whenever they do, you watch and see, there won't be so many wrecks.
I wish they had them now.
And do you know, Texas, of course, has wonderful highways, but Tennessee has the best highways?
Really?
What kind of road did they have when you were growing up there?
We had pikes.
They called them pikes.
And they were made out of pine gravel.
Well, was a pike like what we call a highway?
Yeah, uh-huh.
And when it rained, all that stuff just packed together.
You see, it didn't get muddy.
And that's the kind of sidewalks people had.
Where I was born and reared,
I was born and married out of the house that I was born in.
My daddy had all around the house, and he had three or four barns, and that kind of walkways to the barns.
It was nothing in the world but more of a fine dust-like.
And you wet that, and you cemented together.
It didn't get muddy.
What kind of road were you in, Brian?
Same kind over here?
just like this, went through, narrow.
But the road, the old Bryan Highway, you know where the old Bryan Highway is?
I've heard about it, but I don't know exactly where it is.
Well, it goes, it went kind of around Bryan.
You mean it didn't go through it?
Mm-mm.
Went kind of, wasn't much to go through of Bryan.
I've heard that, too.
Went kind of around it.
Well, I'll tell you where it goes.
You know, like if you are going in to Bryan, let me see, where is that turn?
It kind of makes a turn, and there's a road going this way.
Well, that's the old Bryan Highway.
Oh, I see.
Do you remember when they, you know, did this other, put this other thing in?
Oh, yeah.
When was that?
Oh, I don't remember what, yeah.
And I remember when they built the overpass.
You know the overpass going on to Brown?
I remember when they built that.
Daddy helped to build that.
You see it's got the railroad goes over that.
And he helped to build that, that track across that.
Oh, really?
Mm-hmm.
And the old Brown Highway, when you got to that,

where the old place is why you can see some of it now the old brown highway went all the way around i know what you're talking about yeah i know what you're talking about that's the way it went i know i know exactly what you're talking about right now i don't think there's anything to it except sort of uh remains of it you know it's pretty badly torn up well now i think all it's used through that old highway is where people that live back out in there

it's a way to get in and out to their houses because i know there is some trailer houses that set back off of there in fact people that i know that bought land and put trailer houses out there and that's all that it is it's not kept up it's just kept up by individuals you know the county don't have to keep it up now anything else uh
So what time is it?
It's 25 to 6.
Is there anything else you want to say?
This is plenty for me.
I can tell you another improvement that I have seen more than anything is in the schools.
Of course, I guess one thing, people didn't have the money.
to do with, just take like here.
People will say, we don't have a top-notch school because we don't have the resources.

You see, after they moved the oil tanks out of here, done away with so much railroading, I've seen the time you'd go to P&M Bank, and you'd have to stand there for, they'd be lined up, clear back down to the drugstore.
Really?
And we had better schools then than we do now.
They wouldn't want me to say that, but that's the truth.
Because we had more money.
We have to take secondary of everything.
We have to take teachers that can't get a job nowhere else.
There's no school nowhere, hardly, that will work a teacher now unless they've got two degrees.
That's true, yeah.
Well, we learned about that in some of the education courses
Well, you just take it this way.
When the boys, of course, you know yourself, when you finish high school, you've got to take a test to get in college.
And they claim that Hearn has less percentage of boys and girls in college because they can't make the grade to get in there.
That wouldn't surprise me at all.

surprised me and and i see a big difference in in the school and in the method of teaching what was the method of teaching say when you went to college well now i'll tell you it hasn't changed too much in the method of teaching in their way of teaching uh one day i told john we was talking about classes and uh
I was telling John about an English teacher that I had in college.
Oh, me, his name was White.
And he was hard, hard, hard.
And I said, of course, your desk don't sit that way.
But I said, our desk began this way.
And he said, that's the way ours does.
And I was shocked.
I said, oh, you're kidding.
He said, no, I'm not.
I said, well, maybe I'm not too far behind yet.
That's the way they'll do it.
You couldn't copy.
the way the desk set.
And when John told me, he said, well, that's the way ours set.
Ours is that way now, too.
Staggered?
Yeah.
And I said that that's the way ours was.
And there's one thing in college now they do.
You see, they grade now by points.
We graded.
You got 85 or you got 90.
You got nothing.
There was no points.
It wasn't.
graded down into points.
What was the high school like?
Huh?
What was the high school like?
Well, in our school, there was one big room, and everybody sit in that room.
But in the lower grades, while they had little annex rooms, like the first grade and on up,
Let's see, on up to the sixth, I think, because the seventh and eighth and ninth and on through that way.
We'd go down all that room.
I think that old schoolhouse is still standing there.
I know the last time I was in Tennessee, I always go to that old schoolhouse.
And, oh, it's huge because this was a heavy...

community I mean it was a lot of people there and I guess there's maybe 250 students in all there's a whole lot in that day and down at the front is where we went down for classes and everybody else sit back here you could sit up there and listen if you wanted to of course everybody we used to that we knew nothing but that we studied and I
This school that I went to, I graduated from 12th grade.
And I was 18.
No, I wasn't 18 when I graduated.
And I started college in 1910.
I started, I went to Teachers College.
And that college today is a, oh, we,
It was a big college then.
I think there's about maybe 1,500 or more.
And now they have added to it, and it's, well, I think they've got about between four and 4,500, over 4,000.
They started out with it being teacher's college, and it wasn't but a year or two until anything you want to take up.
Now, when I started, I majored the first,

year i majored in english i was going to make a teacher and then i changed no i no yes i did i changed majors then to home ec and all they were strict oh you think it was more strict than they are now oh yeah i think so because you see that comes again with the modern times with so many things to do with we went to
We went to school.
There wasn't cars for us to get in.
All cars was coming in, I understand.
How did you get around?
Well, the school was in town, and there was buses running to take the children that lived in town or something, maybe that boarded or something.
I stayed at the dormitory.
And the dormitory was just horrible.
It was about as far as from here to DeJulius.
The college was in the center, and the girls was on one side and the boys on the other.
Sunday evening, I sat there in the car.
I didn't go upstairs.
I didn't feel like it.
And there is the boys' dormitory right across there.
There's the girls'.
Well, when I grew up, they wouldn't have nothing like that.
Because of the morality viewpoint then?
Then there comes the morality viewpoint of it again.
People would have thought that would have just been terrible.
And another thing, we had at 10 o'clock, everybody had to be in.
Lights had to go out.
Lights had to be out at 10 o'clock.
And more people went to church then.
There's more of people now.
The population is greater.
But I don't think people go to church like they used to.
I bet you, you're just young, but I bet you, you see a difference.
Yeah, I do.
And then when I went to college, once a week, we had assembly.
We went in, and the dean of this college
He made a talk, and they had prayer.
We'd sing school songs, and sometimes they'd sing religious songs, and then they'd have prayer.
And, of course, now I think that's one of the ugliest things that's ever happened in a schoolroom when they stopped having prayer.
Because that you're one thing and I'm another,
That prayer shouldn't affect that.
And I think that we certainly owe that much to our Lord that's been so good to us.
Yeah, I agree.
Okay, do you have anything else you'd like to add?
Because it's getting pretty late and we need to conclude this.
What was the last thing I said?
I think the last thing we were talking about... That we ought to give the Lord...
Right, right.
I had forgotten myself for a second.
Well...

When any of this class lives to be 83 years old, I feel like that they'll be able, and I hope that they'll be able, especially by going to A&M, that they can give a comment on the past life that they have lived.
And it will be worthwhile to some students.
Really a great idea.
Okay.
Do you have anything else you'd like to add?
Okay, if that's pretty well.
I certainly appreciate you doing this for me.
And thank you for taking the time out of your day to sit down and talk with me.
I really appreciate this.
Thank you very much.
Well, I wish I could have done more, but maybe that'll help you some.
I think it's just going to be fantastic.
Thank you very much.
